Anyway, I believe the datastax interface you need to adapt to `Flux` is this:

```java
import com.google.common.util.concurrent.ListenableFuture;

public interface PagingIterable&lt;S extends PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt;, T&gt; extends Iterable&lt;T&gt; {

    boolean isExhausted();

    boolean isFullyFetched();

    int getAvailableWithoutFetching();

    ListenableFuture&lt;PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt;&gt; fetchMoreResults();

    T one();

}
```

This can be easily adapted to `Flux` by implementing the following adapter:
```java
import java.util.concurrent.Executor;
import com.google.common.util.concurrent.ListenableFuture;

class Adapter&lt;S extends PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt;, T&gt; implements Consumer&lt;FluxSink&lt;T&gt;&gt; {

    private final PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt; result;
    private final Executor executor;

    public Adapter(PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt; result, Executor executor) {
        this.result = result;
        this.executor = executor;
    }

    @Override
    public void accept(FluxSink&lt;T&gt; sink) {
        for (var permits = result.getAvailableWithoutFetching(); permits &gt; 0; permits--) {
            if (sink.isCancelled()) {
                return;
            } else {
                sink.next(result.one());
            }
        }

        assert result.isExhausted() : &quot;current batch was read in full&quot;;

        if (result.isFullyFetched()) {
            sink.complete();
        } else {
            result.fetchMoreResults().addListener(() -&gt; this.accept(sink), executor);
        }
    }
}
```

And providing a method that does the actual adaptation:
```java
private static &lt;S extends PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt;, T&gt; Flux&lt;T&gt; adaptToFlux(PagingIterable&lt;S, T&gt; resultSet, Executor executor) {
    return Flux.create(new Adapter&lt;&gt;(resultSet, executor));
 }
```
For testing purposes, we can implement a dummy `ResultSet` to validate the logic of our `Adapter` like so:
```java
class DummyResultSet implements PagingIterable&lt;DummyResultSet, String&gt; {

    static final int AVAILABLE_WITHOUT_FETCHING = 32;

    private final ListeningExecutorService listeningExecutorService;
    private final int totalSize;

    private int consumedFromAvailable = 0;
    private int index = 0;

    public DummyResultSet(int totalSize, ListeningExecutorService listeningExecutorService) {
        this.totalSize = totalSize;
        this.listeningExecutorService = listeningExecutorService;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean isExhausted() {
        return consumedFromAvailable &gt;= AVAILABLE_WITHOUT_FETCHING;
    }

    @Override
    public boolean isFullyFetched() {
        return index &gt;= totalSize;
    }

    @Override
    public int getAvailableWithoutFetching() {
        return Math.min(totalSize - index, AVAILABLE_WITHOUT_FETCHING);
    }

    @Override
    public ListenableFuture&lt;PagingIterable&lt;DummyResultSet, String&gt;&gt; fetchMoreResults() {
        return listeningExecutorService.submit(() -&gt; {
            consumedFromAvailable = 0;
            return this;
        });
    }

    @Override
    public String one() {
        consumedFromAvailable++;
        index++;
        return String.valueOf(index);
    }

    @Override
    public Iterator&lt;String&gt; iterator() {
        return IntStream.range(index + 1, getAvailableWithoutFetching())
            .dropWhile(i -&gt; isExhausted())
            .peek(
                i -&gt; {
                    consumedFromAvailable++;
                    index = i;
                })
            .mapToObj(Objects::toString).iterator();
    }
}
```

We can then write a simple test to conclude everything is working like so:
```java
public static void main(String[] args) {

    final var threadFactory = new ThreadFactory() {

        final AtomicInteger id = new AtomicInteger();

        @Override
        public Thread newThread(Runnable runnable) {
            final var th = new Thread(runnable);
            th.setName(&quot;test-adapter-&quot; + id.getAndIncrement());
            th.setDaemon(true);
            return th;
        }
    };

    final var datastaxExecutor = MoreExecutors.listeningDecorator(Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor(threadFactory));
    //final var datastaxExecutor = MoreExecutors.newDirectExecutorService();
    final var fluxExecutor = MoreExecutors.directExecutor();

    final var resultSet = new DummyResultSet(100 * 1_000_000 + 1, datastaxExecutor);
    final var flux = adaptToFlux(resultSet, fluxExecutor);

    System.out.println(flux.blockLast());
}
```
And now the conclusion. `datastaxExecutor` is the executor used by the driver internally. If it is a form of `DirectExecutor`, meaning emissions from `Flux` will be executed on the same `Thread`, then this can be a problem. But since it deals with IO, I would assume it is some dedicated `Executor` backed by a thread pool or a NIO handling `Thread`. If that is the case, then `fluxExecutor` can be `directExecutor` which means the emissions of the values from the `ResultSet` would happen on `datastaxExecutor`. If, however, both `datastaxExecutor` and `fluxExecutor` are forms of `DirectExecutor`s, then you will get a `StackOverflow` which is understandable, given the fact that the `Flux` will emit values eagerly on the same `Thread` descending in the stack deeper and deeper with each fetch of the data.
Therefore, if you can safely conclude `datastaxExecutor` used by the driver is always async, then `fluxExecutor` can remain `direct`. If not, you must provide some dedicated `Executor` as `fluxExecutor` to avoid `StackOverflow`. That&#39;s it.

